Startup Investment Analysis¶

Project Summary¶

My goal was to explore the Shark Tank dataset and uncover insights about the kinds of businesses that pitched, the deals that were made, and the behavior of the sharks themselves. I wanted to go beyond simple numbers and actually visualize the trends that shaped the show season by season.

The first step was understanding the structure of the data. Each row represents a pitch, with details such as the startup’s name, industry, valuation asked, whether a deal was secured, and if so, the investment amount and equity involved. On top of that, the dataset tracks the individual contributions of each shark, the presence of guest sharks, and even U.S. viewership numbers per episode. That gave me a wide scope to analyze not just deals, but also audience trends and entrepreneurial demographics.

I built different charts to cover the dataset from multiple angles. Some of them were straightforward, like the proportion of deals versus no deals, or the total investments made per season. Others revealed negotiation dynamics, such as how much equity founders asked for compared to what they actually gave up. Industry-level analysis highlighted which sectors were most represented and which attracted the most funding, while city-level charts showed where entrepreneurs were coming from.

I also focused on the sharks themselves. By aggregating their individual investments, I could see who was the most active investor and who preferred to be more selective. Comparing average equity taken revealed differences in negotiation style. I even looked at how many sharks joined in each deal and how guest sharks participated over the seasons.

On the demographic side, I studied the average age of entrepreneurs and found most were in their twenties and thirties, although older founders weren’t uncommon. When I added in U.S. viewership trends, I could connect the show’s popularity with deal activity, noticing spikes in both investment and audience during certain seasons.

Visualizations¶

1. Deals vs No Deals¶

Insight: Majority of pitches do secure a deal, showing the competitive nature of Shark Tank.

In [25]:
dataset['Got Deal'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', color=['green','red'])
plt.title("Deals vs No Deals")
plt.xlabel("Got Deal")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.show()

2. Total Investment per Season¶

Insight: Some seasons saw significantly higher total investments, reflecting growth in show popularity and bigger deals.

In [28]:
dataset.groupby('Season Number')['Total Deal Amount'].sum().plot(kind='bar')
plt.title("Total Investment per Season")
plt.ylabel("Investment ($)")
plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, pos: f'{int(x):,}'))
plt.show()

3. Average Valuation Requested per Season¶

Insight: Entrepreneurs consistently ask for higher valuations as the show progresses.

In [30]:
dataset.groupby('Season Number')['Valuation Requested'].mean().plot(kind='line', marker='o')
plt.title("Average Valuation Requested per Season")
plt.ylabel("Valuation ($)")
plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, pos: f'{int(x):,}'))
plt.show()

4. Top Industries by Pitch Count¶

Insight: Food, Lifestyle, Fashion dominate the pitch landscape.

In [32]:
dataset['Industry'].value_counts().head(15).plot(kind='bar')
plt.title("Top Industries by Pitch Count")
plt.ylabel("Number of Pitches")
plt.show()

5. Total Deal Amount by Industry¶

Insight: Some industries attract much higher funding even if pitch counts are lower.

In [35]:
dataset.groupby('Industry')['Total Deal Amount'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False).head(15).plot(kind='bar')
plt.title("Total Deal Amount by Industry")
plt.ylabel("Investment ($)")
plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(ticker.FuncFormatter(lambda x, pos: f'{int(x):,}'))
plt.show()

6. Average Equity Asked vs Equity Given¶

Insight: Entrepreneurs usually give up more equity than they initially offered.

In [36]:
dataset[['Original Offered Equity','Total Deal Equity']].mean().plot(kind='bar')
plt.title("Average Equity Asked vs Equity Given")
plt.ylabel("Equity %")
plt.show()

7. Distribution of Entrepreneurs’ Average Age¶

Conclusion¶

  1. Most pitches do not result in deals, showing how selective the sharks are despite the large number of startups featured.

  2. Total investment and valuations have increased over seasons, reflecting both the growing scale of startups and the popularity of the show.

  3. Food, Health, and Consumer Goods dominate pitch volume, but investment is concentrated in a smaller set of industries with high growth potential.

  4. Entrepreneurs usually give up more equity than they initially offer, highlighting the sharks’ strong negotiating position.

  5. Mark Cuban consistently emerges as the biggest investor, while other sharks display more selective patterns of investment.
  6. Most entrepreneurs are in their twenties and thirties, underlining Shark Tank’s role in supporting young founders, though older entrepreneurs are also present.
  7. Audience viewership and deal activity often align, suggesting that the seasons with higher engagement also coincide with larger or more frequent deals.
